# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: allmusic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] The AllMusic review commented: "The mid-'70s were a prime time for tenor saxophonist Warne Marsh, and this 1976 studio session is one of his best dates from this portion of his career. ...
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] Marsh's sophisticated solo work shines no matter what the setting".
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] *The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide* said: "*All Music* is one of the best places to hear Marsh at work".
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] In *JazzTimes* Chris Kelsey wrote: "The late tenor saxophonist Warne Marsh played with a spontaneous, seat-of-the-pants creativity that puts today’s young, book-learned jazzers to shame. ...
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] *All Music* (Nessa) is a straightahead blowing date from 1976 featuring Marsh backed by a redoubtable rhythm section ...
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] Both Levy and Hanna are top-drawer bop stylists, and Marsh is one of the all-time greats at the top of his game.
[src:allmusic/all-music-album] Definitely not just for Tristo-philes or Marsh completists".
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] The book's back cover touts that the book contains ratings for close to 20,000 albums and 1,700 musician biographies.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] Artists are listed alphabetically and include some of the following: birth and death dates, classification (vocals, guitar, drums, etc.), a biography, a discography.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] The discography listings include a five star rating, the music label it was released on, and the date as well as possibly reviews of certain albums.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] These reviews are done by "respected critics" from *Jazz Times* and *Coda*.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] There are also thirty essays on different styles along with "top lists" and extensive charts on the evolution/lineage of the jazz.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] Writing for the now defunct website Jazz Review, Mark E.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] The added features are welcomed, since they give readers a "close-up view of the artists" within the jazz culture.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-jazz] The essays in particular are "exceptionally well researched and written".
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-the-blues] The book's third edition was released in April 2003 and was edited by Vladimir Bogdanov, Chris Woodstra and Stephen Thomas Erlewine.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-the-blues] The book's back cover touts that the book contains ratings for close to 9,000 album and 935 musician biographies.
[src:allmusic/all-music-guide-to-the-blues] Artists are set up alphabetically and include some of the following: birth and death dates, classification (vocals, guitar, drums, etc.), a biography, a discography.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] AllMovie was founded by popular-culture archivist Michael Erlewine, who also founded AllMusic and AllGame.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] The AllMovie database was licensed to tens of thousands of distributors and retailers for point-of-sale systems, websites and kiosks.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] The AllMovie database is comprehensive, including basic product information, cast and production credits, plot synopsis, professional reviews, biographies, relational links and more.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] AllMovie data is accessed on the web at the AllMovie website.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] It was also available via the AMG LASSO media recognition service, which can automatically recognize DVDs.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] In late 2007, TiVo Corporation acquired AMG for a reported $72 million.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] The AMG consumer facing web properties AllMusic, AllMovie and AllGame were sold by Rovi in August 2013 to All Media Network, LLC.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] The buyers also include the original founders of SideReel and Ackrell Capital investor Mike Ackrell.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] RhythmOne offices are located in San Francisco, California, and Ann Arbor, Michigan, United States.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] In the spring of 2024, AllMovie announced that they have moved to a different data provider.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] The site added a "collections" feature for organizing films (e.g.
[src:allmusic/allmovie] *Star Wars* films in the "Skywalker Saga") and information on where films can be streamed, but removed elements including professional reviews and DVD information.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] AllMusic was launched as *All-Music Guide* by Michael Erlewine, a "compulsive archivist, noted astrologer, Buddhist scholar, and musician." He became interested in using computers for his astrological work in the mid-1970s and founded a software company, Matrix, in 1977.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In the early 1990s, as compact discs (CDs) replaced LPs and cassettes as the dominant format for recorded music, Erlewine purchased what he thought was a CD of early recordings by Little Richard.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] After buying it, he discovered it was a "flaccid latter-day rehash." Frustrated with the labeling, he researched using metadata to create a music guide.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 1990, in Big Rapids, Michigan, he founded *All Music Guide* with a goal to create an open-access database that included every recording "since Enrico Caruso gave the industry its first big boost".
[src:allmusic/allmusic] The first *All Music Guide*, published in 1992, was a 1,200-page reference book, packaged with a CD-ROM, titled *All Music Guide: The Best CDs, Albums & Tapes: The Expert's Guide to the Best Releases from Thousands of Artists in All Types of Music*.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] Its first online version, in 1994, was a text-based Gopher site.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] It moved to the World Wide Web as web browsers became more user-friendly.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] Erlewine hired a database engineer, Vladimir Bogdanov, to design the *All Music Guide* framework, and recruited his nephew, writer Stephen Thomas Erlewine, to develop editorial content.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 1993, Chris Woodstra joined the staff as an engineer.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] A "record geek" who had written for alternative weeklies and fanzines, his main qualification was an "encyclopedic knowledge of music".
[src:allmusic/allmusic] AllMusic developed a list of 1,400 subgenres of music, a feature that became central to the site's utility.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In a 2016 article in *Tedium*, Ernie Smith wrote, "AllMusic may have been one of the most ambitious sites of the early-internet [sic] era—and it's one that is fundamental to our understanding of pop culture.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] Because the thing is, it doesn't just track reviews or albums.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] It tracks styles, genres, and subgenres, along with the tone of the music and the platforms on which the music is sold.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 1996, seeking to further develop its web-based businesses, Alliance Entertainment Corp. bought All Music from Erlewine for a reported $3.5 million.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] Alliance filed for bankruptcy in 1999, and its assets were acquired by Ron Burkle's Yucaipa Equity Fund.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 1999, All Music relocated from Big Rapids to Ann Arbor, Michigan, where the staff expanded from 12 to 100 people.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] By February of that year, 350,000 albums and two million tracks had been cataloged.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In late 2007, AllMusic was purchased for $72 million by TiVo Corporation (known as Macrovision at the time of the sale and as Rovi from 2009 until 2016).
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 2012, AllMusic removed all of Bryan Adams' info from the site per a request from the artist.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In 2015, AllMusic was purchased by BlinkX, later known as RhythmOne.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] The AllMusic database is powered by a combination of MySQL and MongoDB.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] The All Media Network produced the *All Music Guide: The Definitive Guide* (at first released as *The Experts' Guide*), which includes a series of publications about various music genres.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] It was followed by the *Required Listening* series and annual guides.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] Vladimir Bogdanov is the president and the main editor of the series.
[src:allmusic/allmusic] In August 2007, *PC Magazine* included AllMusic in its "Top 100 Classic Websites" list.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is home to the University of Michigan, the oldest university in the state.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Its economy is primarily focused on high technology, with numerous startup companies drawn to the area due to the university's robust research and development activities.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Founded in 1824 with American settlers from the East Coast, it was incorporated as a city in 1851.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It is the principal city of its metropolitan area, and it is also included in the Detroit–Warren–Ann Arbor combined statistical area as well as the Great Lakes megalopolis.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The region was once inhabited by several Native American tribes, the most prominent being the Anishinaabe people of the Three Fires: the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Potawatomi founded two villages in the area of what is now Ann Arbor in about 1774.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other tribes that inhabited the area included the Wyandots and Sauk.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These peoples established several trails that converged on present-day Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The land that included Washtenaw County was ceded to the U.S. by the Odawa, Ojibwe, Potawatomi, and Wyandot in the Treaty of Detroit of 1807.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor was founded in 1824 by land speculators John Allen and Elisha Walker Rumsey.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] On May 25, 1824, the town plat was registered with Wayne County as the Village of Annarbour, the earliest known use of the town's name.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Allen and Rumsey decided to name it for their wives, both named Ann, and for the stands of bur oak in the 640 acres (260 ha) of land they purchased for $800 (equivalent to $23,000 in 2025) from the federal government at $1.25 per acre.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The local Ojibwa named the settlement *kaw-goosh-kaw-nick*, after the sound of Allen's sawmill.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor became the seat of Washtenaw County in 1827 and was incorporated as a village in 1833.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Land Company, a group of speculators, set aside 40 acres (16 ha) of undeveloped land and offered it to the state of Michigan as the site of the state capitol, but lost the bid to Lansing.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1837, the property was accepted instead as the site of the University of Michigan.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Since the university's establishment in the city in 1837, the histories of the University of Michigan and Ann Arbor have been closely linked.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The town became a regional transportation hub in 1839 with the arrival of the Michigan Central Railroad, and a north–south railway connecting Ann Arbor to Toledo and other markets to the south was established in 1878.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Throughout the 1840s and the 1850s settlers continued to come to Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] While the earlier settlers were primarily of British ancestry, the newer settlers also consisted of Germans, Irish, and Black people.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1851, Ann Arbor was chartered as a city, though the city showed a drop in population during the Depression of 1873.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It was not until the early 1880s that Ann Arbor again saw robust growth, with new immigrants from Greece, Italy, Russia, and Poland.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor saw increased growth in manufacturing, especially in milling.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor's Jewish community also grew after the turn of the 20th century, and its first and oldest synagogue, Beth Israel Congregation, was established in 1916.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Following a 1956 vote, the city of East Ann Arbor merged with Ann Arbor to encompass the eastern sections of the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1960, Ann Arbor voters approved a $2.3 million bond issue (equivalent to $19 million in 2024) to build the current city hall, which was designed by architect Alden B.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 1995, the building was renamed the Guy C.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Municipal Building in honor of the longtime city administrator who championed the building's construction.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] During the 1960s and 1970s, the city gained a reputation as an important center for liberalism (liberal politics), and a locus for left-wing activism, anti-Vietnam War activism, and student activism.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The first major meetings of the national left-wing campus group Students for a Democratic Society occurred in Ann Arbor in 1960; in 1965, the city was home to the first U.S. teach-in against the Vietnam War.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] During the ensuing 15 years, many countercultural and New Left enterprises sprang up and developed large constituencies within the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These influences washed into municipal politics during the early and mid-1970s when three members of the Human Rights Party (HRP) won city council seats on the strength of the student vote.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] During their time on the council, HRP representatives fought for measures including pioneering antidiscrimination ordinances, measures decriminalizing marijuana possession, and a rent-control ordinance.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Two religious-conservative institutions were created in Ann Arbor; the Word of God (established in 1967), a charismatic inter-denominational movement; and the Thomas More Law Center (established in 1999).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Since 1998, Ann Arbor is also the home office of the Anthroposophical Society in the United States, an organization dedicated to supporting the community of those interested in the inner path of schooling known as anthroposophy, developed by Rudolf Steiner.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] From 1967 to its closing in 1990, Ann Arbor hosted KMS Fusion, the world's first company to pursue fusion power via the inertial confinement fusion method.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In the past several decades, Ann Arbor has grappled with the effects of sharply rising land values, gentrification, and urban sprawl stretching into outlying countryside.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] On November 4, 2003, voters approved a greenbelt plan under which the city government bought development rights on agricultural parcels of land adjacent to Ann Arbor to preserve them from sprawling development.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Since then, a vociferous local debate has hinged on how and whether to accommodate and guide development within city limits.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor consistently ranks in the "top places to live" lists published by various mainstream media outlets every year.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2016, the city changed mayoral terms from two years to four.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Until 2017, City Council held annual elections in which half of the seats (one from each ward) were elected to 2-year terms.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These elections were staggered, with each ward having one of its seats up for election in odd years and its other seat up for election in even years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Beginning in 2018 the city council has had staggered elections to 4-year terms in even years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] This means that half of the members (one from each ward) are elected in presidential election years, while the other half are elected in mid-term election years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] To facilitate this change in scheduling, the 2017 election elected members to terms that lasted 3-years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2020, partly as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, the city government opened several downtown streets to pedestrians, limiting their use by motor vehicles to emergency vehicles during summertime weekends.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In addition to providing a large pedestrian mall, these changes allow restaurants to use more of the sidewalks and part of the street for outdoor seating.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These changes were popular enough that in 2021 the city council extended the dates from March to November, continuing the schedule of cordoning off cars from Thursday evening until Monday morning.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is located along the Huron River, which flows southeast through the city on its way to Lake Erie.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It is the central core of the Ann Arbor, MI Metropolitan Statistical Area, which consists of the whole of Washtenaw County, but is also a part of the Metro Detroit Combined Statistical Area designated by the U.S.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] While it borders only Townships, the built-up nature of the sections of Pittsfield and Ypsilanti townships between Ann Arbor and the city of Ypsilanti make the two effectively a single urban area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The landscape of Ann Arbor consists of hills and valleys, with the terrain becoming steeper near the Huron River.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The elevation ranges from about 750 feet (230 m) along the Huron River to 1,015 feet (309 m) on the city's west side, near the intersection of Maple Road and Pauline Blvd.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is nicknamed "Tree Town", both due to its name and to the dense forestation of its parks and residential areas.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city contains more than 50,000 trees along its streets and an equal number in parks.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Into the early 2000s, the emerald ash borer has destroyed many of the city's approximately 10,500 ash trees.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city contains over 160 municipal parks ranging from small neighborhood green spots to large recreation areas such as Buhr Park.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several large city parks and a university park border sections of the Huron River.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Fuller Recreation Area, near the University Hospital complex, contains sports fields, pedestrian and bike paths, and swimming pools.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Opened in the summer of 2014, the city-funded Ann Arbor Skatepark is a 30,000 sq ft (2,787.1 m2) skatepark located within Veterans Memorial Park.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to the Washtenaw County-owned County Farm Park.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Nichols Arboretum, owned by the University of Michigan, is a 123-acre (50 ha) arboretum that contains hundreds of plant and tree species.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It is on the city's east side, near the university's Central Campus.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Located across the Huron River just beyond the university's North Campus is the university's Matthaei Botanical Gardens, which contains 300 acres of gardens and a large tropical conservatory.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several other green spaces around Ann Arbor are privately owned or owned by government agencies such as Ann Arbor Public Schools.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The cityscape of Ann Arbor is heavily influenced by the University of Michigan, with 22% of downtown and 9.4% of the total land owned by the university.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The downtown Central Campus contains some of the oldest extant structures in the city—including the President's House, built in 1840—and separates the South University District from the other three downtown commercial districts.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These other three districts, Kerrytown, State Street, and Main Street are contiguous near the northwestern corner of the university.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Major landmarks in downtown Ann Arbor include the Michigan Theater, The Diag, and Tower Plaza, a 26-story condominium building that is the city's tallest building.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Downtown is also home to several Fairy Doors and other public art installations.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Three commercial areas south of downtown include the areas near I-94 and Ann Arbor-Saline Road, Briarwood Mall, and the South Industrial area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other commercial areas include the Arborland/Washtenaw Avenue and Packard Road merchants on the east side, the Plymouth Road area in the northeast, and the Westgate/West Stadium areas on the west side.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Downtown contains a mix of 19th- and early-20th-century structures and modern-style buildings, as well as a farmers' market in the Kerrytown district.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's commercial districts are composed mostly of two- to four-story structures, although downtown and the area near Briarwood Mall contain a small number of high-rise buildings.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor's residential neighborhoods contain architectural styles ranging from classic 19th- and early 20th-century designs to ranch-style houses.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Among these homes are a number of kit houses built in the early 20th century.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Contemporary-style houses are farther from the downtown district.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Surrounding the University of Michigan campus are houses and apartment complexes occupied primarily by student renters.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The 19th-century buildings and streetscape of the Old West Side neighborhood have been preserved virtually intact; in 1972, the district was listed on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP), and it is further protected by city ordinances and a nonprofit preservation group.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a typically Midwestern humid continental climate (Köppen *Dfa*), which is influenced by the Great Lakes.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] There are four distinct seasons: winters are cold and snowy, with average highs around 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Summers are warm to hot and humid, with average highs around 81 °F (27 °C) and with slightly more precipitation.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Spring and autumn are transitional between the two.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The area experiences lake effect weather, primarily in the form of increased cloudiness during late fall and early winter.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The monthly daily average temperature in July is 72.6 °F (22.6 °C), while the same figure for January is 24.5 °F (−4.2 °C).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Temperatures reach or exceed 90 °F (32 °C) on 10 days, and drop to or below 0 °F (−18 °C) on 4.6 nights.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Precipitation tends to be the heaviest during the summer months, but most frequent during winter.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Snowfall, which normally occurs from November to April but occasionally starts in October, averages 58 inches (147 cm) per season.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The lowest recorded temperature was −23 °F (−31 °C) on February 11, 1885, and the highest recorded temperature was 105 °F (41 °C) on July 24, 1934.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has seen consistent growth in population between all decennial censuses since 1860 with the exception of the 2010 census which reported almost no growth from the previous census.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] As of the 2020 U.S. census, there were 123,851 people and 49,337 households residing in the city, with a population density of 4,391.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,695.7/km2).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The racial makeup of the city including Hispanics in the racial categories was 67.6% White, 6.8% Black, 0.2% Native American, 15.7% Asian, 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander, 1.8% from other races, and 7.9% from two or more races.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race made up 5.5% of the population.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a small population of Arab Americans, including students as well as local Lebanese and Palestinians, and a large community of Japanese nationals.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] According to the 2022 American Community Survey estimates, out of 49,337 households, 33.8% were married-couple households, 9.8% were cohabiting couple households, 26.1% had a male householder with no spouse present, and 30.4% had a female householder with no spouse present.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] 18.4% of the households had individuals under the age of 18 living in them, and 20.1% had individuals over age 65 living in them.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The average household size was 2.22 people and the average family size was 2.78 people.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The median age was 25.9; 12.2% of the population was under age 18, and 12.3% was age 65 or older.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The median household income in 2022 was $78,740 (versus the U.S. national figure of $75,149), with family households having a median income of $126,292.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The per capita income for the city was $52,276, which is higher than the U.S. national per capita income of $41,261.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Males working full-time jobs had median earnings of $86,970 compared to $61,543 for females.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Further, 3.5% of minors and 7.7% of seniors were below the poverty line.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] According to the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) program in 2022, Ann Arbor had 371 reported violent crimes (which include homicide, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault) and 2069 reported property crimes (which include arson, burglary, larceny-theft, and motor vehicle theft).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] With a violent crime rate of 309.5 per 100,000 people, the city's violent crime rate is lower than Michigan's rate of 461 per 100,000 people and the U.S. national rate of 380.7 per 100,000 people.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] However, Ann Arbor's property crime rate, at 1726.0 per 100,000 people, is higher than Michigan's property crime rate of 1536.8 per 100,000 people and lower than the U.S. national property crime rate of 1954.4 per 100,000 people.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan shapes Ann Arbor's economy significantly.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It employs about 30,000 workers which includes about 12,000 in the medical center.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other employers are drawn to the area by the university's research and development money, and by its graduates.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] High tech, health services and biotechnology are other major components of the city's economy; numerous medical offices, laboratories, and associated companies are located in the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Automobile manufacturers, such as General Motors and Visteon, also employ residents.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] High tech companies have located in the area since the 1930s, when International Radio Corporation introduced the first mass-produced AC/DC radio (the Kadette, in 1931) as well as the first pocket radio (the Kadette Jr., in 1933).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Firms include Arbor Networks (provider of Internet traffic engineering and security systems), Arbortext (provider of XML-based publishing software), JSTOR (the digital scholarly journal archive), Truven Health Analytics, and ProQuest, which includes UMI.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Duo Security, a cloud-based access security provider of two-factor authentication, is headquartered in Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] It was formerly a unicorn and continues to be headquartered in Ann Arbor after its acquisition by Cisco Systems.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In November 2021, semiconductor test equipment company KLA Corporation opened a new North American headquarters in Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is the home to Internet2 and the Merit Network, a not-for-profit research and education computer network.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Both are located in the South State Commons 2 building on South State Street.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to a secondary office of Google's AdWords program—the company's primary revenue stream.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] As of 2022, Ann Arbor is home to more than twenty video game and XR studios of varying sizes.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city plays host to a regional chapter of the International Game Developers Association (IGDA) which hosts monthly meetups, presentations, and educational events.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is the home of many research and engineering centers, including the Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory that is operated by NOAA and the Michigan Tech Research Institute.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other research centers sited in the city are the United States Environmental Protection Agency's National Vehicle and Fuel Emissions Laboratory and the Toyota Technical Center.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to National Sanitation Foundation International (NSF International), the nonprofit non-governmental organization that develops generally accepted standards for a variety of public health related industries and subject areas.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Non-high tech companies in Ann Arbor include Domino's Pizza, headquartered on Domino's Farms, a 271-acre (110 ha) Frank Lloyd Wright-inspired complex just northeast of the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Another Ann Arbor-based company is Zingerman's Delicatessen, which serves sandwiches and has developed businesses under a variety of brand names.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Avfuel, a global supplier of aviation fuels and services, is headquartered in Ann Arbor as is Pinkerton, a detective and private security firm.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Many cooperative enterprises were founded in the city; among those that remain are the People's Food Co-op and the Inter-Cooperative Council at the University of Michigan, a student housing cooperative founded in 1937.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] There are also three cohousing communities—Sunward, Great Oak, and Touchstone—located immediately to the west of the city limits.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several performing arts groups and facilities are on the University of Michigan's campus, as are museums dedicated to art, archaeology, and natural history and sciences.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Founded in 1879, the University Musical Society is an independent performing arts organization that presents over 60 events each year, bringing international artists in music, dance, and theater.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Since 2001 Shakespeare in the Arb has presented one play by Shakespeare each June, in a large park near downtown.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Regional and local performing arts groups not associated with the university include the Ann Arbor Civic Theatre, the Arbor Opera Theater, the Ann Arbor Symphony Orchestra, The Ark, and Performance Network Theatre.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] State Theatre and the adjacent Michigan Theater are a movie palace and a performing arts center, respectively.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Another unique piece of artistic expression in Ann Arbor is the fairy doors.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These small portals are examples of installation art and can be found throughout the downtown area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Hands-On Museum, an interactive science center, is located in a renovated and expanded historic downtown fire station.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Art Center is a nonprofit that organizes art activities and exhibitions.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Aside from the Ann Arbor District Library, which maintains four branch outlets in addition to its main downtown building, and being the home to the Gerald R.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ford Presidential Library, Ann Arbor ranks first among U.S. cities in the number of booksellers and books sold per capita.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several annual events—many of them centered on performing and visual arts—draw visitors to Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] One such event is the Ann Arbor Art Fairs, a set of four concurrent juried fairs held on downtown streets.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Scheduled on Thursday through Sunday of the third week of July, the fairs draw upward of half a million visitors.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Another is the Ann Arbor Film Festival, held during the third week of March, which receives more than 2,500 submissions annually from more than 40 countries and serves as one of a handful of Academy Award–qualifying festivals in the United States.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] A person from Ann Arbor is called an "Ann Arborite", and many long-time residents call themselves "townies".
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city itself is often called "A²" ("A-squared") or "A2" ("A two") or "AA", "The Deuce" (mainly by Chicagoans), and "Tree Town".
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is a major center for college sports, most notably at the University of Michigan.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several well-known college sports facilities exist in the city, including Michigan Stadium, the largest American football stadium and the third-largest stadium of any kind in the world with a capacity of 107,601.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The stadium is colloquially known as "The Big House" due to its status as the largest American football stadium.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Crisler Center and Yost Ice Arena play host to the school's basketball (both men's and women's) and ice hockey teams, respectively.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Concordia University, a member of the NAIA, also fields sports teams.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In semi-professional sports Ann Arbor is represented in the NPSL by AFC Ann Arbor, a soccer club founded in 2014 who call themselves The Mighty Oak.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] As the county seat of Washtenaw County, the Washtenaw County Trial Court (22nd Circuit Court) is located in Ann Arbor at the Washtenaw County Courthouse on Main Street.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The 15th Michigan district court, which serves only the city itself, is located within the Ann Arbor Justice Center, immediately next to city hall.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan and Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit are also located in downtown Ann Arbor, at the federal building on Liberty Street.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In the Michigan Legislature, the city is split between Districts 23, 33, 47, and 48 in the Michigan House of Representatives.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In the Michigan Senate, Ann Arbor is covered by Districts 14 and 15.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is within the 6th congressional district, currently represented by Debbie Dingell.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor has a council–manager form of government, with 11 voting members: the mayor and 10 city council members.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Each of the city's five wards are represented by two council members, with the mayor elected at-large during midterm years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Half of the council members are elected in midterm years, with the other in general election years.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The mayor is the presiding officer of the city council and has the power to appoint all council committee members as well as board and commission members, with the approval of the city council.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The current mayor of Ann Arbor is Christopher Taylor, a Democrat who was elected as mayor in 2014.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Day-to-day city operations are managed by a city administrator chosen by the city council.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] While Democrats, as of 2024, hold the mayorship and all ten council seats, Ann Arbor has two major political factions.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] A major source of this local divide is differences in views on the city's growth.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Public schools are part of the Ann Arbor Public Schools (AAPS) district.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] AAPS has one of the country's leading music programs.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] For the 2021–2022 school year, 17,070 students were enrolled in the Ann Arbor Public Schools.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Notable schools include Pioneer, Huron, Skyline, Community high schools, Pathways to Success Academic Campus, and Ann Arbor Open School.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The district has a preschool center with both free and tuition-based programs for preschoolers in the district.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The University High School, a "demonstration school" with teachers drawn from the University of Michigan's education program, was part of the school system from 1924 to 1968.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is home to several private schools, including Clonlara School, Michigan Islamic Academy, and Greenhills School, a prep school.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also home to several charter schools such as Central Academy (Michigan) (PreK–12) of the Global Educational Excellence (GEE) charter school company.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan dominates the city of Ann Arbor, providing the city with its college town character.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] University buildings are located in the center of the city and the campus is directly adjacent to the State Street and South University downtown areas.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other local colleges and universities include Concordia University Ann Arbor, a Lutheran liberal-arts institution.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2000, the Ave Maria School of Law, a Roman Catholic law school established by Domino's Pizza founder Tom Monaghan, opened in northeastern Ann Arbor; the school moved to Ave Maria, Florida in 2009, and the Thomas M.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Cooley Law School acquired the former Ave Maria buildings for use as a branch campus.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Publications in the city include the *Ann Arbor Observer*, a free monthly local magazine; and *Current*, a free entertainment-focused alt-weekly.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The *Ann Arbor Business Review* covers local business in the area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] *Car and Driver* magazine and *Automobile Magazine* are also based in Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan is served by many student publications, including the independent *Michigan Daily* student newspaper, which reports on local, state, and regional issues in addition to campus news.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Four major AM radio stations based in or near Ann Arbor are WAAM 1600, a conservative news and talk station; WLBY 1290, a business news and talk station; WDEO 990, Catholic radio; and WTKA 1050, which is primarily a sports station.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's FM stations include NPR affiliate WUOM 91.7; country station WWWW 102.9; and adult-alternative station WQKL 107.1.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Freeform station WCBN-FM 88.3 is a local community radio/college radio station operated by the students of the University of Michigan featuring noncommercial, eclectic music and public-affairs programming.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is also served by public and commercial radio broadcasters in Ypsilanti, the Lansing/Jackson area, Detroit, Windsor, and Toledo.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor is part of the Detroit television market.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] WPXD channel 31, the owned-and-operated Detroit outlet of the ION Television network, is licensed to the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Until its sign-off on August 31, 2017, WHTV channel 18, a MyNetworkTV-affiliated station for the Lansing market, was broadcast from a transmitter in Lyndon Township, west of Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Community Television Network (CTN) is a city-provided cable television channel with production facilities open to city residents and nonprofit organizations.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Detroit and Toledo-area radio and television stations also serve Ann Arbor, and stations from Lansing and Windsor, Ontario, can be seen in parts of the area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The University of Michigan Health System (UMHS) includes University Hospital, C.S.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Mott Children's Hospital and Women's Hospital in its core complex.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] UMHS also operates out-patient clinics and facilities throughout the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The area's other major medical centers include a large facility operated by the Department of Veterans Affairs in Ann Arbor, and Saint Joseph Mercy Hospital in nearby Superior Township.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city provides sewage disposal and water supply services, with water coming from the Huron River and groundwater sources.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] There are two water-treatment plants, one main and three outlying reservoirs, four pump stations, and two water towers.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] These facilities serve the city, which is divided into five water districts.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city's water department also operates four dams along the Huron River—Argo, Barton, Geddes, and Superior—of which Barton and Superior provide hydroelectric power.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city also offers waste management services, with Recycle Ann Arbor handling recycling service.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other utilities are provided by private entities.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Electrical power and gas are provided by DTE Energy.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] AT&T Inc. is the primary wired telephone service provider for the area.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Cable TV service is primarily provided by Comcast.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] A plume of the industrial solvent dioxane is migrating under the city from the contaminated Gelman Sciences, Inc. property on the westside of Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] As of 2021, the average measured concentration was found to be 201.19 ppb, with the maximum being 6.000 ppm.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] While the United States Environmental Protection Agency does not impose a federal limit on the level of the contaminant allowed in drinking water, the World Health Organization suggests a limit of 35 ppb.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Gelman plume is a potential threat to one of the City of Ann Arbor's drinking water sources, the Huron River, which flows through downtown Ann Arbor.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The streets in downtown Ann Arbor conform to a grid pattern, though this pattern is less common in the surrounding areas.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Major roads branch out from the downtown district to the highways surrounding the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The city is belted by three freeways: Interstate 94 (I-94), which runs along the southern and western portion of the city; U.S.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Highway 23 (US 23), which primarily runs along the eastern edge of Ann Arbor; and M-14, which runs along the northern edge of the city.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Other nearby highways include US 12 (Michigan Avenue), M-17 (Washtenaw Avenue), and M-153 (Ford Road).
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Several of the major surface arteries lead to the I-94/M-14 interchange in the west, US 23 in the east, and the city's southern areas.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Washtenaw County Border-to-Border Trail connects Ann Arbor to Ypsilanti, mostly along the Huron River, for pedestrians, bicycles and other non-motorized transportation.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Area Transportation Authority (AAATA), which brands itself as "TheRide", operates public bus services throughout the city and nearby Ypsilanti.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The AAATA operates the Blake Transit Center on Fourth Ave. in downtown Ann Arbor, and the Ypsilanti Transit Center.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] A separate zero-fare bus service operates within and between the University of Michigan campuses.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] In 2019, 36% of trips in Ann Arbor were taken by walking, biking or transit.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Since April 2012, the "AirRide" connects to Detroit Metro Airport a dozen times a day.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Michigan Flyer, a service operated by Indian Trails, cooperates with AAATA for their AirRide and additionally offers bus service to East Lansing.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Greyhound Lines provides intercity bus service.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Megabus has direct service to Chicago, Illinois, while a bus service is provided by Amtrak Thruway for rail passengers making connections to services in East Lansing and Toledo, Ohio.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Amtrak, which provides service to the city at the Ann Arbor Train Station, operates the *Wolverine* train between Chicago and Pontiac via Detroit.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The present-day train station neighbors the city's old Michigan Central Depot, which was renovated as a restaurant in 1970.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] The Ann Arbor Railroad passes through the city and provides freight service but no passenger service.
[src:allmusic/ann-arbor-michigan] Ann Arbor Municipal Airport is a small, city-run general aviation airport located just south of the city.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids was settled in 1855 by brothers George and Zera French.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As the village of Leonard, at the intersection of Elm and Stewart streets, it became the seat of Mecosta County on February 11, 1859, but local lumbermen knew the site as Big Rapids.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] On September 29, 1859, the Leonard post office was renamed Big Rapids.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids was platted on November 3, 1859, surrounding the courthouse site of Leonard.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The unincorporated community of Big Rapids was first cited on June 10, 1861, rather than Leonard, when the Mecosta County board of supervisors mentioned their seat of government, and in 1865 was consistently cited throughout the year.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids was incorporated as a city in 1869.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 4.562 square miles (11.82 km2), of which 4.445 square miles (11.51 km2) is land and 0.117 square miles (0.30 km2) (2.56%) is water.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids is in northwestern Mecosta County in central Michigan.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] It is 56 miles (90 km) north of Grand Rapids and 42 miles (68 km) south of Cadillac, both via Highway 131.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The city sits along the Muskegon River, which passes Ferris State University and the local middle school on its way southwest to Lake Michigan.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As with most of the area, Big Rapids lies on an ancient seabed and has a sandy subsoil which lies above an iron ore base.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The city levies an income tax of 1 percent on residents and 0.5 percent on nonresidents.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The Fred Meijer White Pine Trail, a 92-mile (148 km) multi-use trail from Grand Rapids to Cadillac, passes through Big Rapids.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids' population peaked in the 1980s.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Since the 1980s, Big Rapids has lost over 46% of its population.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There are a number of reasons for the decline, one being the decline in enrollment at Ferris State University.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As of the 2020 census, there were 7,727 people, 2,996 households, and 1,270 families residing in the city.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The population density was 1,738.36 inhabitants per square mile (671.2/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,700 housing units at an average density of 832.40 per square mile (321.4/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The median age in the city was 23.7 years.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 16.0% of residents were under the age of 18 and 11.0% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] For every 100 females, there were 84.9 males.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 81.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 99.5% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.5% lived in rural areas.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Of the 2,996 households, 22.4% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Of all households, 24.6% were married-couple households, 25.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 40.0% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] About 42.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.2%, and the rental vacancy rate was 15.2%.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As of the 2024 American Community Survey, there were 3,133 estimated households in Big Rapids with an average of 2.06 persons per household.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The city has a median household income of $43,858.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Approximately 34.1% of the city's population lives at or below the poverty line.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Big Rapids has an estimated 62.3% employment rate, with 26.9% of the population holding a bachelor's degree or higher and 94.3% holding a high school diploma.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,610 housing units at an average density of 812.15 per square mile (313.6/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The median age in the city was 22.9 years.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] According to realtor website Zillow, the average price of a home as of March 31, 2026, in Big Rapids is $215,285.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The top five reported languages (people were allowed to report up to two languages, thus the figures will generally add to more than 100%) were English (98.2%), Spanish (0.7%), Indo-European (0.4%), Asian and Pacific Islander (0.5%), and Other (0.2%).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As of the 2010 census, there were 10,601 people, 3,330 households, and 1,323 families residing in the city.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The population density was 2,429.19 inhabitants per square mile (937.9/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,623 housing units at an average density of 830.20 per square mile (320.5/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 87.97% White, 6.75% African American, 0.70% Native American, 1.47% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.57% from some other races and 2.52% from two or more races.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 2.38% of the population.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,330 households, of which 22.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 22.9% were married couples living together, 12.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 60.3% were non-families.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 36.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The average household size was 2.22 and the average family size was 2.88.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The median age in the city was 21.8 years.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 12.5% of residents were under the age of 18; 54% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 15.9% were from 25 to 44; 11.2% were from 45 to 64; and 6.5% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The gender makeup of the city was 51.0% male and 49.0% female.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] As of the 2000 census, there were 10,849 people, 3,388 households, and 1,473 families residing in the city.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The population density was 2,555.55 inhabitants per square mile (986.7/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,654 housing units at an average density of 860.72 per square mile (332.3/km2).
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 83.57% White, 10.63% African American, 0.73% Native American, 2.24% Asian, 0.04% Pacific Islander, 0.50% from some other races and 2.30% from two or more races.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 1.83% of the population.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] There were 3,388 households out of which 25.5% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 26.5% were married couples living together, 14.3% have a female householder with no husband present, and 56.5% were non-families.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 35.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.8% have someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 2.93.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] In the city the population was spread out with 15.2% under the age of 18, 51.0% from 18 to 24, 17.3% from 25 to 44, 9.1% from 45 to 64, and 7.4% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] For every 100 females there were 109.4 males.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 110.4 males.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The median income for a household in the city was $20,192, and the median income for a family was $28,629.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Males have a median income of $30,341 versus $19,770 for females.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] The per capita income for the city was $10,719.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] 35.0% of the population and 19.2% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] Out of the total people living in poverty, 29.3% were under the age of 18 and 11.6% were 65 or older.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] This climatic region has large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.
[src:allmusic/big-rapids-michigan] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Big Rapids has a humid continental climate, abbreviated "Dfb" on climate maps.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The first issue of *Billboard* was published in Cincinnati, Ohio, by William Donaldson and James Hennegan on November 1, 1894.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Initially it covered the advertising and bill-posting industry and was known as ***Billboard Advertising***.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] At the time, billboards, posters, and paper advertisements placed in public spaces were the primary means of advertising.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Donaldson handled editorial and advertising, while Hennegan, who owned Hennegan Printing Co., managed magazine production.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The first issues were just eight pages long.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The paper had columns such as The Bill Room Gossip and The Indefatigable and Tireless Industry of the Bill Poster.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] A department for agricultural fairs was established in 1896.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The *Billboard Advertising* publication was renamed ***The Billboard*** in 1897.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] After a brief departure over editorial differences, Donaldson purchased Hennegan's interest in the business in 1900 for $500 (equal to $15,500 today) to save it from bankruptcy.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] On May 5, Donaldson changed the publication from a monthly to a weekly paper with a greater emphasis on breaking news.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] He improved editorial quality and opened new offices in New York, Chicago, San Francisco, London, and Paris, and also refocused the magazine on outdoor entertainment such as fairs, carnivals, circuses, vaudeville, and burlesque shows.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] A section devoted to circuses was introduced in 1900, followed by more prominent coverage of outdoor events in 1901.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] *Billboard* also covered topics including regulation, professionalism, economics and new shows.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] It had a "stage gossip" column covering the private lives of entertainers, a "tent show" section covering traveling shows and a subsection called "Freaks to Order".
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] As railroads became more developed, *Billboard* enabled a mail-forwarding system for traveling entertainers.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The location of an entertainer was tracked in the paper's Routes Ahead column, and then *Billboard* would receive mail on the star's behalf and publish a notice in its Letter-Box column that it had mail for him or her.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] This service was first introduced in 1904 and became one of *Billboard*'s largest sources of profit and celebrity connections.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] By 1914, 42,000 people were using the service.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] It was also used as the official address of traveling entertainers for draft letters during World War I.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In the 1960s, when the service was discontinued, *Billboard* was still processing 1,500 letters per week.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 1920, Donaldson controversially hired black journalist James Albert Jackson to write a weekly column devoted to black performers.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] According to *The Business of Culture: Strategic Perspectives on Entertainment and Media*, the column identified discrimination against black performers and helped validate their careers.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Jackson was the first black critic at a national magazine with a predominantly white audience.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] According to his grandson, Donaldson also established a policy against identifying performers by their race.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The jukebox industry continued to grow through the Great Depression and was advertised heavily in *Billboard*, which led to even more editorial focus on music.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The proliferation of the phonograph and radio also contributed to its growing music emphasis.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] *Billboard* published the first music hit parade on January 4, 1936 and introduced a Record Buying Guide in January 1939.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 1940, it introduced Chart Line, which tracked the best-selling records, and was followed by a chart for jukebox records in 1944 called Music Box Machine.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] By the 1940s, *Billboard* was more of a music-industry specialist publication.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The number of charts that it published grew after World War II, as new music interests and genres became popular.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] It had eight charts by 1987, covering different genres and formats, and 28 charts by 1994.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] By 1943, *Billboard* had about 100 employees.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The magazine's offices moved to Brighton, Ohio in 1946, then to New York City in 1948.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] A five-column tabloid format was adopted in November 1950 and coated paper was first used in *Billboard*'s print issues in January 1963, allowing for photojournalism.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Over time, subjects that *Billboard* covered outside of the music world formed the basis of separate publications: *Funspot* magazine was created in 1957 to cover amusement parks and *Amusement Business* was created in 1961 to cover outdoor entertainment.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In January 1961, *The Billboard* was renamed ***Billboard Music Week*** to emphasize its newly exclusive interest in music.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Two years later, it was renamed to simply *Billboard*.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] According to *The New Business Journalism*, by 1984, Billboard Publications was a "prosperous" conglomerate of trade magazines, and *Billboard* had become the "undisputed leader" in music-industry news.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In the early 1990s, *Billboard* introduced *Billboard Airplay Monitors*, a publication for disc jockeys and music programmers.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] By the end of the 1990s, *Billboard* dubbed itself the "bible" of the recording industry.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 1987, *Billboard* was sold again to Affiliated Publications for $100 million.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Billboard Publications Inc. became a subsidiary of Affiliated Publications called BPI Communications.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] As BPI Communications, it acquired *The Hollywood Reporter*, *Adweek*, *Marketing Week* and *Mediaweek*, and also purchased Broadcast Data Systems, a high-tech firm for tracking music airtime.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Private investors from Boston Ventures and BPI executives repurchased a two-thirds interest in Billboard Publications for $100 million, and more acquisitions followed.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 1993, it created a division known as Billboard Music Group for music-related publications.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 1994, Billboard Publications was sold to Dutch media conglomerate Verenigde Nederlandse Uitgeverijen (VNU) for $220 million.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] VNU acquired the Clio Awards in advertising and the National Research Group in 1997, as well as *Editor & Publisher* in 1999.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In July 2000, it paid $650 million to the publisher Miller Freeman.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] BPI was combined with other entities in VNU in 2000 to form Bill Communications Inc.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] By the time CEO Gerald Hobbs retired in 2003, VNU had grown substantially larger, but had a great deal of debt from the acquisitions.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] An attempted $7 billion acquisition of IMS Health in 2005 prompted protests from shareholders that halted the deal; it eventually agreed to an $11 billion takeover bid from investors in 2006.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] VNU changed its name to Nielsen in 2007, the namesake of a company that it had acquired for $2.5 billion in 1999.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] New CEO Robert Krakoff divested some of the previously owned publications, restructured the organization and planned some acquisitions before dying suddenly in 2007.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] He was subsequently replaced by Greg Farrar.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Nielsen owned *Billboard* until 2009, when it was one of eight publications sold to e5 Global Media Holdings. e5 was formed by investment firms Pluribus Capital Management and Guggenheim Partners for the purpose of the acquisition.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The following year, the new parent company was renamed Prometheus Global Media.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Three years later, Guggenheim Partners acquired Pluribus' share of Prometheus and became the sole owner of *Billboard*.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In December 2015, Guggenheim Digital Media spun out several media brands, including *Billboard*, to its own executive Todd Boehly.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The assets operate under the Hollywood Reporter-Billboard Media Group, a unit of the holding company Eldridge Industries.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Timothy White was appointed editor-in-chief in 1991, a position that he held until his unexpected death in 2002.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] White wrote a weekly column promoting music with "artistic merit" while criticizing music with violent or misogynistic themes, and also reworked the publication's music charts.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Rather than relying on data from music retailers, new charts used data from store checkout scanners obtained by Nielsen SoundScan.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] White also wrote in-depth profiles on musicians, but was replaced by Keith Girard, who was subsequently fired in May 2004.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Girard and a female employee filed a $29 million lawsuit alleging that *Billboard* fired them unfairly with an intent to damage their reputations and that they experienced sexual harassment, a hostile work environment and a financially motivated lack of editorial integrity.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Email evidence suggested that human resources were given special instructions to watch minority employees.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The case was settled out of court in 2006 for an undisclosed sum.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In the 2000s, economic decline in the music industry dramatically reduced readership and advertising from *Billboard*'s traditional audience.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The publication's staff and ownership were also undergoing frequent changes.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 2004, Tamara Conniff became the first female and youngest-ever executive editor at *Billboard* and led its first major redesign since the 1960s, designed by Daniel Stark and Stark Design.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] During Conniff's tenure, *Billboard*'s newsstand sales jumped 10%, ad pages climbed 22% and conference registrations rose 76%.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 2005, *Billboard* expanded its editorial outside the music industry into other areas of digital and mobile entertainment.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] In 2006, after leading *Billboard*'s radio publication, former ABC News and CNN journalist Scott McKenzie was named editorial director across all *Billboard* properties.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Conniff launched the *Billboard* Women in Music event in 2007.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Bill Werde was named editorial director in 2008, and was followed by Janice Min in January 2014, also responsible for editorial content at *The Hollywood Reporter*.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The magazine became more of a general-interest music-news source rather than solely an industry trade, covering more celebrity and fashion news.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Min hired Tony Gervino as editor although he did not have a background in the music industry.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Gervino was appointed editor-in-chief in April 2014.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] An NPR item covered a leaked version of *Billboard*'s annual survey, which it said had more gossip and focused on less professional topics than had prior surveys.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] For example, the magazine polled readers on a lawsuit that singer Kesha filed against her producer, alleging sexual abuse.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] A note from Min to the editorial staff indicated that senior vice president of digital content Mike Bruno would head the editorial department.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] On June 15, 2016, BillboardPH, the first *Billboard* chart company in Southeast Asia, mainly in the Philippines, was announced.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] On September 12, 2016, *Billboard* expanded into China by launching *Billboard China* in partnership with Vision Music Ltd.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] On September 23, 2020, it was announced that Penske Media Corporation would assume operations of the MRC Media & Info publications under a joint venture with MRC known as PMRC.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The joint venture includes the management of *Billboard*.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] On January 13, 2024, *Billboard* shared the intent to expand further in Asia by announcing the launch of *Billboard Korea*.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Since 1990 *Billboard* established the *Billboard* Music Awards, an awards ceremony honors top album, artist and single in a number of different music genres which achieved the highest results during the year form sales, streaming, radio airplay, touring, and social engagement.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] The data are taken from *Billboard* and its data partners, including MRC Data and Next Big Sound.
[src:allmusic/billboard-magazine] Through the years, *Billboard* has established several other awards and polls to honor different music genres, live performances, and artists.
